# HardFault Debugging Checklist — {{mcu}} ({{core}})

## Step 1: Read Fault Status Registers

| Register | Address | What It Tells |
|----------|---------|---------------|
| SCB->CFSR | 0xE000ED28 | Combined Configurable Fault Status |
| SCB->HFSR | 0xE000ED2C | HardFault Status |
| SCB->MMFAR | 0xE000ED34 | MemManage Fault Address (if MMARVALID) |
| SCB->BFAR | 0xE000ED38 | BusFault Address (if BFARVALID) |

## Step 2: Decode CFSR Bits

### UsageFault (bits 16-25)
| Bit | Name | Meaning |
|-----|------|---------|
| 25 | DIVBYZERO | Division by zero (if DIV_0_TRP enabled) |
| 24 | UNALIGNED | Unaligned access |
| 19 | NOCP | No coprocessor (FPU not enabled) |
| 18 | INVPC | Invalid PC load on return |
| 17 | INVSTATE | Invalid EPSR state (Thumb bit) |
| 16 | UNDEFINSTR | Undefined instruction |

### BusFault (bits 8-15)
| Bit | Name | Meaning |
|-----|------|---------|
| 15 | BFARVALID | BFAR holds valid address |
| 13 | LSPERR | Lazy state preservation error |
| 12 | STKERR | Stacking error on exception entry |
| 11 | UNSTKERR | Unstacking error on exception return |
| 10 | IMPRECISERR | Imprecise data access (address unknown) |
| 9 | PRECISERR | Precise data access (BFAR valid) |
| 8 | IBUSERR | Instruction bus error |

### MemManage (bits 0-7)
| Bit | Name | Meaning |
|-----|------|---------|
| 7 | MMARVALID | MMFAR holds valid address |
| 4 | MSTKERR | Stacking error |
| 3 | MUNSTKERR | Unstacking error |
| 1 | DACCVIOL | Data access violation |
| 0 | IACCVIOL | Instruction access violation |

## Step 3: Read Stacked PC/LR

```c
// In HardFault_Handler, read stacked registers:
// R0-R3, R12, LR, PC, xPSR are pushed to stack
// PC = stack[6] — the faulting instruction
// LR = stack[5] — the return address
```

## Step 4: Common Causes on {{mcu}}

| Fault Pattern | CFSR Value | Likely Cause |
|---------------|-----------|--------------|
| PRECISERR + BFARVALID | 0x00000200 + 0x00008000 | NULL pointer dereference (BFAR=0x00000000) |
| UNALIGNED | 0x01000000 | Unaligned LDRD/STRD/LDM/STM |
| UNDEFINSTR | 0x00010000 | Stack overflow corrupted code |
| IMPRECISERR | 0x00000400 | Write to invalid memory (hard to trace) |
| IBUSERR | 0x00000100 | PC jumped to non-executable region |
| STKERR | 0x00001000 | Stack pointer below valid RAM |

## Step 5: Stack Overflow Detection

1. Check SP value — if below `0x1FFF8000` (SRAM_L start), stack overflow
2. Check stack canary pattern at bottom of stack
3. Stack size is only 1.5KB — local arrays >128B are high risk
